			</div>
<p>UNIFIED CHALLENGE 2014 directly informed pressing Army problems and conceptual gaps, while providing a venue to inform the development of the new Army functional concepts.  As Gen. David G. Perkins, U.S. Training and Doctrine Command's (TRADOC) Commanding General, states in the preface to the Army Operating Concept, every Army professional should "think clearly about the problem of future armed conflict."<span class="endnoteRef">[6]</span>  Experimentation seeks to address this problem by asking the fundamental questions concerning the feasibility of future concepts and capabilities to enable the Army to continue to prevent, shape, and win against a variety of future threats across the spectrum of conflict.</p>
<p>The results and procedural lessons learned from 2014 experimentation informs Army and Centers of Excellence efforts in 2015, beginning with the UNIFIED CHALLENGE 15.1 Seminar Wargame occurring from March 16-27 at the Mission Command Battle Lab at Fort Leavenworth, Kansas.</p>
<p class="BubbleTitleSection">About the Joint and Army Experimentation Division</p>
<p>ARCIC's Joint and Army Experimentation Division (JAED) leads, designs, manages, integrates, and assesses Army experiments to support current and future capabilities development efforts.  In coordination with other Service, Joint, Inter-governmental and Multinational partners, deliver Army-level experimentation results that produce coordinated Doctrine, Organization, Training, Material, Leadership, Personnel, and Facilities (DOTMLPF) solutions.  JAED leads the Army experimentation program on behalf of the Headquarters of the Department of the Army (HQDA).<span class="endnoteRef">[7]</span></p>
